    <main class="container">
      <section class="cards-grid" aria-live="polite">
        <article class="card" data-category="vitals">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/legacy-heirloom.html">
            <h2>Legacy Heirloom</h2>
            <p>
              Born in 1955 in Boston, Massachusetts, Monty carries the name and expectations
              of Preston Montgomery Jones III&mdash;a title that opens any gala door even if he no longer recalls why it matters.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="vitals">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/beliefs-and-persona.html">
            <h2>Beliefs &amp; Persona</h2>
            <p>
              Proud Founder &amp; Chairman of Jones Capital (rebranded from Montgomery Capital) and fixture on elite boards, Monty believes decorum is
              the final currency. Twice-yearly church visits and tax-deductible generosity form his proof of virtue.
            </p>
            <blockquote>
              “Decorum is the final currency.”
            </blockquote>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="education-career">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/education-foundations.html">
            <h2>Education Foundations</h2>
            <p>
              Groton School alumnus and Harvard graduate in Finance (minor in "Connections"). Co-founded the Harvard
              Entrepreneurial Society and secured a ghostwritten MBA thesis titled <em>Ethics and the Executive Imagination</em>.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="education-career">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/corporate-conquests.html">
            <h2>Corporate Conquests</h2>
            <p>
              Dubbed a leveraged-buyout pioneer of the 1980s boom, Monty reshaped dying companies for profit&mdash;even firing
              a VP over plastic cutlery to “curate morale.”
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="education-career">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/notorious-ventures.html">
            <h2>Notorious Ventures</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>1983:</strong> Bought a restaurant mural thinking it was a lost Monet, rebranded it as performance art.</li>
              <li><strong>1992:</strong> Hosted the luxury Charity Safari where a zebra named Jones benefitted most.</li>
              <li><strong>2001:</strong> Launched AskMonty.com, a week-long tech experiment undone by job requests.</li>
              <li><strong>2006:</strong> Memoir <em>Capital with Compassion</em> declared minimum wage “a polite fiction.”</li>
            </ul>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="education-career">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/strategic-overseer.html">
            <h2>Strategic Overseer</h2>
            <p>
              Though officially retired in the 2010s, Monty continues meddling as a self-described “strategic overseer,”
              guiding from the shadows without accountability.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="family">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/muffy-montgomery.html">
            <h2>Muffy Montgomery Jones</h2>
            <p>
              Newport aristocrat and Monty’s late wife. Seven years after her passing, he still credits her for cementing two old-money dynasties under the Jones banner.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="family">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/preston-iv.html">
            <h2>Preston IV – “P-Money”</h2>
            <p>
              Influencer heir Preston Montgomery Jones IV mixes vintage suits with tone-deaf captions. Viral moment: “Building generational wealth—emotionally.”
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="family">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/tiffany-montgomery-blythe.html">
            <h2>Tiffany Montgomery Jones</h2>
            <p>
              Founder of Wings of the Forgotten, an NGO for ethically relocating endangered moths. Board meetings include themed cocktails and rebranded Jones family monograms.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="family">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/gloria-baby-gloria.html">
            <h2>Gloria “Baby Gloria”</h2>
            <p>
              Youngest child and brand ambassador for the Jones name. Featured in <em>Town &amp; Country</em>’s “Best Dressed Under Ten.”
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="family">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/extended-lineage.html">
            <h2>Extended Lineage</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Eleanor Montgomery Jones:</strong> Matriarch hosting “intimate” dinners for 120 and penning heirloom-quality thank-you notes.</li>
              <li><strong>Preston Montgomery Jones II:</strong> Father who perfected credit-taking acquisitions; passed away surrounded by stock tickers.</li>
              <li><strong>Caroline Montgomery Jones:</strong> Philanthropic painter with a self-showcasing foundation.</li>
              <li><strong>Uncle Bradford Jones:</strong> Vineyard owner, progressive voter, and family renegade.</li>
            </ul>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/debutante-duel-1974.html">
            <h2>The Debutante Duel (1974)</h2>
            <p>
              Proposed to two debutantes—simultaneously by person and telegram—leading to lawsuits and a temporary waltz ban.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/harvard-episode.html">
            <h2>The Harvard Episode</h2>
            <p>
              In the late 1970s Monty claimed to have “invented synergy.” No one has successfully disproven the boast.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/art-market-adventure.html">
            <h2>The Art Market Adventure</h2>
            <p>
              Mistook a restaurant mural for a lost Monet in 1983. Declared the blunder “social commentary” and kept the painting proudly.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/charity-safari.html">
            <h2>The Charity Safari</h2>
            <p>
              1992’s air-conditioned wildlife fundraiser for elites. Primary beneficiary: a zebra named Jones.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/dancing-legend.html">
            <h2>Ballroom Legend</h2>
            <p>
              Monty’s ballroom prowess is whispered about across Newport—precision footwork, effortless lifts, and late-night
              EDM/pop dance parties where he swaps the waltz for neon strobes without missing a beat.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/memoir-tour.html">
            <h2>The Memoir Tour</h2>
            <p>
              2006 publicity tour for <em>Capital with Compassion</em>, featuring the infamous quote that minimum wage is “a polite fiction.”
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/newport-incident-2015.html">
            <h2>The Newport Incident (2015)</h2>
            <p>
              Mistook the mayor’s wife for a server, offering a tip for “refilling the caviar.” The apology was handwritten on gilt stationery.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="personal-life">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/digital-revival-2020s.html">
            <h2>The Digital Revival (2020s)</h2>
            <p>
              Attempted to digitize family archives, accidentally publishing decades of private correspondence and ledgers—still online with a dramatization disclaimer.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="vitals">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/faith-and-ritual.html">
            <h2>Faith &amp; Ritual</h2>
            <p>
              Attends St. Bartholomew’s twice yearly (Christmas and Easter) and touts it as evidence of devout faith and impeccable breeding.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>

        <article class="card" data-category="vitals">
          <a class="card-link" href="expanded/charitable-calculus.html">
            <h2>Charitable Calculus</h2>
            <p>
              Champions the moral value of charity, though his generosity is measured meticulously in tax deductions and social capital.
            </p>
          </a>
        </article>
